### Broader Tool Design: Configurability and Defaults

Given these varying contexts, how should a performance analysis tool be designed?

**1. Configurable by Metric Class:** The tool must expose sensitivity and specificity as configurable parameters per analysis type. However, it should never expose raw statistical jargon (like "Z-Score Threshold" or "Isolation Forest Contamination"). It must expose user-centric outcomes: a slider ranging from *"Alert on subtle deviations"* to *"Only alert on massive outages."*

**2. The Defaults Must Earn Trust:** Out of the box, defaults must fiercely favor **high specificity (low noise)**. Trust is the currency of observability. If a new tool generates three false positives in its first week, engineers will route its emails to `/dev/null`. A tool must earn the right to be tuned toward sensitivity by first proving its baseline alerts are highly accurate.

**3. Owned by Service Owners:** Central Platform or SRE teams can establish baseline templates, but the **Service Owners (the engineers holding the pager)** must have the final override. A team running a Tier-1 payment gateway will tune their parameters very differently than a team running a Tier-3 internal batch job. The person feeling the pain of the false positive must control the dial.

