### Organizational Dynamics: Fear vs. Fatigue

Ultimately, the way an organization tunes these dials is rarely about mathematics; it is Conway's Law in action. The sensitivity threshold is a mirror reflecting a company's psychological safety.

**Over-alerting (The Blame Culture):**
Teams over-alert when they operate in punitive environments. If an engineer is publicly reprimanded during a post-mortem for "missing a regression," they will engage in Cover-Your-Ass (CYA) monitoring. They crank up the sensitivity so the system flags every minor jitter. The logic is self-preservation: *"I didn't miss the incident; the system caught it, it was just buried in 500 other alerts."* High sensitivity becomes a shield against blame, shifting liability from the human to the inbox, but destroying team velocity in the process.

**Under-alerting (The Burnout Culture):**
Teams under-alert when they are drowning in operational toil. If an architecture is rife with technical debt and management prioritizes feature shipping over stability, the system will constantly flap. To survive their on-call shifts and get some sleep, engineers will systematically numb the anomaly detectors. They optimize for their own sanity over catching regressions, accepting that minor incidents will reach the user simply because they do not have the bandwidth to care.

**The Resolution:** The only way to decouple this human tension from the statistical tool is to separate *anomalies* from *alerts*. Anomaly detection should be highly sensitive, but its output should only be an annotation on a dashboard for Monday morning review. It should only trigger a pager alert if that anomaly is actively burning through a user-facing **Service Level Objective (SLO)**.